<p><b>Sergey Mikhaylovich Prokudin-Gorsky</b> (<a href="/wiki/Russian_language" title="Russian language">Russian</a>: <span class="unicode audiolink" lang="ru" xml:lang="ru"><a href="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e5/Ru-Prokudin-Gorskii.ogg" class="internal" title="Ru-Prokudin-Gorskii.ogg">Серге́й Миха́йлович Проку́дин-Го́рский</a></span><span class="metadata audiolinkinfo" style="cursor:help; vertical-align:super;"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Media_help" title="Wikipedia:Media help">?</a>·<a href="/wiki/File:Ru-Prokudin-Gorskii.ogg" title="File:Ru-Prokudin-Gorskii.ogg">i</a></span>, August 31 <small>[<a href="/wiki/Old_Style_and_New_Style_dates" title="Old Style and New Style dates">O.S.</a> August 19]</small> 1863, Murom, Russian Empire – September 27, 1944, Paris, France) was a Russian <a href="/wiki/Chemist" title="Chemist">chemist</a> and <a href="/wiki/Photography" title="Photography">photographer</a>. He is best known for his pioneer work in <a href="/wiki/Colour_photography" title="Colour photography" class="mw-redirect">colour photography</a> of early 20th century Russia.<sup id="cite_ref-loc_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-loc-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
